{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-js","path":"/posts/use-different-desktop-managers-of-ubuntu","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"id":"514b2e1d-e357-5a01-a6db-5d7cb3ba0079","html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/4b190/ubuntu.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.25%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n          <source\n              srcset=\"/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/8ac56/ubuntu.webp 240w,\n/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/d3be9/ubuntu.webp 480w,\n/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/d00b9/ubuntu.webp 800w\"\n              sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n              type=\"image/webp\"\n            />\n          <source\n            srcset=\"/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/09b79/ubuntu.jpg 240w,\n/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/7cc5e/ubuntu.jpg 480w,\n/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/4b190/ubuntu.jpg 800w\"\n            sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n            type=\"image/jpeg\"\n          />\n          <img\n            class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n            src=\"/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/4b190/ubuntu.jpg\"\n            alt=\"ubuntu logo\"\n            title=\"ubuntu logo\"\n            loading=\"lazy\"\n            style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n          />\n        </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>First of all, X Window Core must be installed, or you won’t be able to use GUI. X Window Core is called “x-window-system-core”. To install any GUI, you should install this first.</p>\n<p>Display manager(Login manager): gdm/kdm/xdm, usually one of them is chosen. To get different desktop manager for ubuntu, just add packages following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>gnome</strong>: ubuntu-desktop</li>\n<li><strong>kde</strong>: kubuntu-desktop</li>\n<li><strong>xfce</strong>: xubuntu-desktop</li>\n</ul>\n<p>With APT, you may type “sudo apt-get install ubuntu-desktop” in the console.</p>\n<p>After the installation, of course, we should set default-display-manager on ubuntu. There are two ways(not including all methods) to try:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Edit file “/etc/X11/default-display-manager”, change display manager name in it and save, then reboot.</li>\n<li>Run “dpkg-reconfigure gdm/kdm/xdm” to switch (gdm for gnome, kdm for kde, xdm for xfce), you will get a menu to choose. Of course you should do this as root, so add “sudo”.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Refer to: <a href=\"http://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=205002\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\">HOWTO: correctly install/remove k/x/ed/ubuntu-desktop packages</a></p>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/use-different-desktop-managers-of-ubuntu","tagSlugs":["/tag/linux-system/","/tag/gui-desktop/"]},"frontmatter":{"date":"2007-04-01T22:30:00.000Z","description":"desktop managers are important to ubuntu GUI, it's useful to learn the method for changing them.","tags":["Linux System","GUI Desktop"],"title":"Use Different Desktop Managers of Ubuntu","socialImage":{"publicURL":"/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/ubuntu.jpg"}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/posts/use-different-desktop-managers-of-ubuntu"}},"staticQueryHashes":["251939775","401334301","825871152"]}